<TYPE>
<P>
Wild Art 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA060290-0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 227614 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 2, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 2; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Smogbusters: At Unocal's recycled auto project at 26th Street and Long 
Beach Avenue in Los Angeles, old smog makers line up to be stripped and 
squashed. Under the program, which began Friday, Unocal will pay owners of 
7,000 vehicles with the model year 1970 and earlier $700 per car for 
demolition. So far, nearly 6,000 appointments have been made. The first to go 
was Dick Rossman's 1964 Cadillac. For a year he had been trying to sell the car 
-- with 311,000 miles on it -- for $250, and Unocal's offer was one he couldn't 
refuse. At right, Jose Flores empties the oil before the Caddy succumbs. IRIS 
SCHNEIDER / Los Angeles Times 
