<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONTROVERSY OVER NEA FUNDS FOR ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The NEA isn't the stock market, no matter how much Fein and Meese would like it 
to be. It's no wonder that 25 years of NEA funding seems interminable to people 
who are always looking for a fast buck and higher return on their investments. 
</P>
<P>
They expect masterworks to be produced and acknowledged in that short space of 
time, when the examples they cite have been around for decades, even centuries. 
The idea that great visual art is what garners the highest bids "at Southeby or 
Christie auctions" is yet another symptom of the malignant Reagan era money 
mentality: the measure of quality is in the price tag. 
</P>
<P>
The proposal to shift NEA funds to education is admirable but redundant. All 
art is, by its very nature, public, inclusive, revealing, enlightening -- in 
other words, educational. 
</P>
<P>
NEA grants aren't "government protection against free consumer choice." Rather, 
they are seed money for artistic gardens which, with diligence and luck, will 
prosper and perhaps, given years of critical and popular consideration, bloom 
into the accepted masterworks of the world and give joy and stimulation to 
everyone. And for the notion that art experts are "feasting off taxpayers' 
dollars" -- well, let's just say that no single artist is getting rich from NEA 
money. The price the government has paid certain military suppliers for a small 
bag of bolts and a toilet seat or two could float an entire colony of artists 
for years. 
</P>
<P>
DAVID DRUMMOND 
</P>
<P>
AUSTIN GRAY 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
