<HEADLINE>
<P>
MONTANA IS SAID TO AGREE TO PACT FOR $14 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Joe Montana, who has quarterbacked the San Francisco 49ers to four Super Bowl 
titles, has reached agreement on a contract extension that would pay him $4.5 
million next season and about $14 million for four years, The National reported 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Montana would become the highest-paid player in team sports, 
surpassing the $3.86 million per year of Don Mattingly of the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
The National said the contract, which would include bonus payments, apparently 
has not been signed. 
</P>
<P>
Montana made a base salary of $1.2 million last season, and without a contract 
extension, he would earn $2.55 million per year the next three years. 
</P>
<P>
According to The National, the contract provides for decreasing earnings, 
scaling down to $4 million in 1991, $3.5 million in 1992 and $2.5 million in 
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
