<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHEVRON PLANS UNLEADED LOW-EMISSIONS GASOLINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK LEE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chevron Corp. is test-marketing a lower-emissions gasoline in Florida and plans 
to introduce a version of it on the West Coast in the near future, Chevron 
dealers said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The new gasoline, to be called Chevron Unleaded Plus, is similar in composition 
to Atlantic Richfield Co.'s EC-1 gasoline, the first of several lower-emissions 
gasolines to hit the market in the last several months, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arco confirmed that it may come out with another reformulated 
gasoline to accompany EC-1 as soon as this fall. EC-1, which was introduced in 
September, is sold to cars that previously used only leaded gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
Arco's new lower-emissions gasoline, code-named EC-X, would be marketed to cars 
that use unleaded gas, possibly as a premium grade such as Shell's new SU 
2000E. 
</P>
<P>
Few other details concerning Chevron's new gasoline were available, and a 
Chevron spokeswoman in San Francisco declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
If Chevron proceeds with plans to market such a gasoline, it will join seven 
other major oil companies marketing some form of so-called reformulated 
gasoline in various parts of the country. Exxon Corp. began selling a 
reformulated gasoline in 20 Eastern and Gulf Coast states on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
At least two more refiners are planning similar introductions. 
</P>
<P>
In an interview, George H. Babikian, president of Arco's refining and marketing 
subsidiary, said the company had not made up its mind yet on how to proceed 
with its new gasoline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
