<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAPAN'S TRADE SURPLUS SHRINKS 70% IN APRIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus declined by 70% in April, the sharpest drop since June, 
1979, due largely to a jump in imports that reflects the expensive tastes of 
Japanese consumers, economists said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The surplus in Japan's current account, the broadest measure of trade in goods 
and services, narrowed to $2 billion in April from $6.58 billion a year earlier 
and $8.13 billion in March. 
</P>
