<HEADLINE>
<P>
EMI MUSIC'S NET PROFIT MORE THAN DOUBLES IN YEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUBE SHIVER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Aided by booming sales at its record labels, EMI Music's profit more than 
doubled from $73.5 million to a record $150.2 million for the year ended March 
31. 
</P>
<P>
The London-based music concern, a unit of the British electronics and music 
conglomerate Thorn EMI PLC, said sales rose from $1.3 billion to a record $1.7 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
The better-than-expected results came amid an overall slowing in music industry 
sales in the United States last year. 
</P>
<P>
But EMI, which formed a joint venture with SBK last year and paid $79.1 million 
for a 50% interest in Chrysalis, has enjoyed surprising success domestically 
with Sinead O'Connor, whose Chrysalis album went to No. 1 in 16 countries, and 
with M. C. Hammer, a rap artist with EMI's Los Angeles-based Capitol Records 
label. Hammer's "Please Don't Hurt 'Em" album ranks No. 2 on the Billboard list 
of top 100 albums. 
</P>
<P>
Besides O'Connor and Hammer, EMI's roster of artists includes Bonnie Raitt, 
Freddie Jackson, Richard Marx, Paul McCartney and Tina Turner. The company now 
claims a 12% share of the worldwide music market. JUBE SHIVER 
</P>
</TEXT>
