<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: COUNTYWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
10% INCREASE SOUGHT FOR POLLUTION FEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ventura County Air Pollution Control District has proposed to hike the cost 
of permits by 10% to businesses that add pollutants to the air, county 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The increase, subject to approval by the County Board of Supervisors, will 
increase fees for oil companies, power companies, gas stations and other 
businesses emitting pollutants and is expected to raise $119,000 annually, said 
Mike Villegas, a district spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
"We're increasing fees and we're changing how we weight some of the 
pollutants," Villegas said. 
</P>
<P>
Fees are being restructured to penalize companies more severely for emitting 
certain pollutants, such as those known to harm the ozone layer, and less for 
others. 
</P>
<P>
Villegas said fees are charged on the basis of the number of pounds per hour of 
pollutants emitted, with different fees being assessed for different 
pollutants. He said most pollutants are assessed at the rate of $43 per pound 
per hour. 
</P>
<P>
The increased revenues will be used to pay the salaries of seven new staff 
members and to finance new programs mandated by the California Clean Air Act of 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
There are now nearly 1,000 businesses with permits. Villegas said he expects 
that number to increase as more businesses move into the area and as county 
pollution standards become stricter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
