<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; 
</P>
<P>
NEW JOURNAL OFFERS STATISTICS GALORE ON HOUSING MARKETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by John O'Dell, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In case your shelf of real estate periodicals isn't overflowing already, a trio 
of industry heavyweights has launched a new one. 
</P>
<P>
The Meyers Group, a Chino-based real estate research and consulting firm, has 
teamed with Brea-based economist Alfred Gobar and Boud Real Estate Information 
Systems, a statistics specialist, to prepare and publish the Southland-oriented 
Real Estate Economic Journal. 
</P>
<P>
Each of the 10 issues each year will concentrate on a single housing market. 
</P>
<P>
Readers of the journal will get supply-and-demand summaries along with 
population, employment growth and building permit data; examinations of trends 
in residential construction and projections of what to expect from the local 
economy and from future home sales will be offered. 
</P>
<P>
The first two issues of the journal already have hit the streets. The inaugural 
book dealt with Riverside County, while the second volume was devoted to the 
Antelope Valley. Next up, the publishers say, is San Diego County. 
</P>
<P>
It won't be Orange County's turn until the ninth issue in November. 
</P>
<P>
The books, priced from $950 to $1,500 an issue (the Orange County volume will 
run $1,250), are aimed at statistics junkies, builders, lenders, speculators 
and anyone else who can benefit from what amounts to an off-the-shelf market 
feasibility report. 
</P>
<P>
Copies of the journal are available at the three Meyers Group offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
